isher=[[McFarland & Company]] |date=2006 |pages=80\u201390 |chapter=Playing the Bad Guy: Grand Theft Auto in the Panopticon |isbn=978-0-7864-2822-9 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite journal |last=Crookes |first=David |title=The Making of Grand Theft Auto III |publisher=United States: [[Imagine Publishing]] |journal=[[Retro Gamer]] |issue=122 |date=November 2013 |pages=58\u201383 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |title=Grand Theft Auto III Game Manual |author=DMA Design |publisher=[[Rockstar Games]] |year=2001 |ref=harv|author-link=DMA Design }}\n*{{cite book |last=Kushner |first=David |authorlink=David Kushner |title=Jacked: The Outlaw Story of Grand Theft Auto |publisher=[[Turner Publishing Company]] |date=3 April 2012 |isbn=978-0-4709-3637-5 |ref=harv |title-link=Jacked: The Outlaw Story of Grand Theft Auto }}\n*{{cite journal |title=The Top 200 Games of All Time |pages=44\u201379 |issue=200 |date=December 2009 |journal=[[Game Informer]] |issn=1067-6392 |oclc=27315596 |ref={{harvid|Game Informer|2009}} }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n*{{Official website}}\n*{{IMDb title|0277723|Grand Theft Auto III}}\n\n{{Portal bar|New York City|Speculative fiction|Video games}}\n{{Grand Theft Auto}}\n{{DMA Design}}\n{{Rockstar Games}}\n{{GDCA GOTY}}\n{{Golden Joystick GOTY}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grand Theft Auto 03}}\n[[Category:2001 video games]]\n[[Category:Action-adventure games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled GameCube games]]\n[[Category:Censored video games]]\n[[Category:Grand Theft Auto III| ]]\n[[Category:Impact of the September 11 attacks on the video game industry]]\n[[Category:Interactive Achievement Award winners]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Motion capture in video games]]\n[[Category:Obscenity controversies in video games]]\n[[Category:Open world video games]]\n[[Category:Organized crime video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 2 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation Network games]]\n[[Category:RenderWare games]]\n[[Category:Rockstar Games]]\n[[Category:Rockstar Vienna games]]\n[[Category:Take-Two Interactive games]]\n[[Category:Video games about revenge]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female antagonists]]\n[[Category:Video games set in 2001]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games with custom soundtrack support]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox games]]\n", "name_user": "IceWelder", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleaned up usingAutoEd, harmonize whitespace in citation templates byscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grand_Theft_Auto_III"}
{"title_page": "2007 Sedgefield by-election", "text_new": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name = Sedgefield by-election\n| type = parliamentary\n| country = United Kingdom\n| seats_for_election = [[Sedgefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Sedgefield]] parliamentary seat\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 2005 United Kingdom general election\n| previous_year = 2005\n| next_election = 2010 United Kingdom general election\n| next_year = 2010\n| election_date = 19 July 2007\n\n| candidate1 = [[Phil Wilson (British politician)|Phil Wilson]]\n| image1 = [[File:Phil Wilson 2015.jpg|90px]]\n| party1 = Labour Party (UK)\n| popular_vote1 = '''12,528'''\n| percentage1 = '''44.8%'''\n| swing1         = {{decrease}}14.1%\n\n| candidate2 = Greg Stone\n| image2 = [[File:No image.svg|90px]]\n| party2 = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n| popular_vote2 = 5,572\n| percentage2 = 19.9%\n| swing2         = {{increase}}8.0%\n\n| candidate3 = Graham Robb\n| image3 = [[File:No image.svg|90px]]\n| party3 = Conservative Party (UK)\n| popular_vote3 = 4,082\n| percentage3 = 14.6%\n| swing3         = {{increase}}0.2%\n| candidate4 = Andrew Spence\n| image4 = [[File:No image wide.svg|95x50px|Blank]]\n| party4 = British National Party\n| popular_vote4 = 2,494\n| percentage4 = 8.9%\n| swing4        = ''New party''\n| candidate5 = Paul Gittins\n| image5 = [[File:No image wide.svg|95x50px|Blank]]\n| party5 = Independent (politician)\n| popular_vote5 = 1,885\n| percentage5 = 6.7%\n| swing5        = ''New party''\n| title = MP\n| posttitle = Subsequent MP\n| before_election = [[Tony Blair]]\n| before_party = Labour Party (UK)\n| after_election = [[Phil Wilson (British politician)|Phil Wilson]]\n| after_party = Labour Party (UK)\n}}\n\n[[Image:SedgefieldConstituency.svg|thumb|Map of Sedgefield]]\nThe '''Sedgefield by-election, 2007''' was a [[by-election]] held on 19 July 2007 for the [[British House of Commons]] constituency of [[Sedgefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Sedgefield]] in [[County Durham]].  The [[2007 Ealing Southall by-election|Ealing Southall by-election]] was also held on 19 July.\n\nThe by-election was triggered when [[Tony Blair]], the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for Sedgefield and former [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]], \"[[Resignation from the British House of Commons|resigned]]\" to become envoy for the international diplomatic [[Quartet on the Middle East]].  To resign as an MP, Blair accepted the office of [[Steward and Bailiff of the Three Hundreds of Chiltern]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/newsroom_and_speeches/press/2007/press_72_07.cfm |work=HM Treasury |title=Three Hundreds of Chiltern |date=2007-06-27 |accessdate=2007-06-27}}</ref> thereby deliberately disqualifying himself from Parliament and causing the by-election.  Blair had held the constituency since its creation for the [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983 election]], and Labour had held its predecessor constituencies since the [[1935 United Kingdom general election|1935 election]].\n\nAccording to [[Sedgefield]] Borough Council, the electorate for the by-election was 67,339 which represents an increase of 673 (1%) on the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]].\n\n==Candidates==\nThe [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] selected [[Phil Wilson (British politician)|Phil Wilson]], a [[public relations]] consultant, local party member and one of the \"Famous Five\" who had promoted [[Tony Blair]]'s first candidacy in 1983. He was chosen from a shortlist of five candidates, including former Minister [[Melanie Johnson]].<ref name=\"famous\">Chris Lloyd, \"[http://www.thisisthenortheast.co.uk/display.var.1518245.0.labour_chooses_one_of_the_famous_five.php Labour chooses one of the 'Famous Five']\", ''[[The Northern Echo]]''</ref> The [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] chose North East regeneration expert Greg Stone, a councillor in [[Newcastle-upon-Tyne]] and former candidate in the [[Vale of York (UK Parliament constituency)|Vale of York]] in the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 election]] and [[Newcastle-upon-Tyne Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle-upon-Tyne Central]] in the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 election]].<ref name=\"famous\"/> The Conservatives stood Graham Robb, a [[public relations]] consultant and former [[radio presenter]], who stood for the party in [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]] in [[Hartlepool (UK Parliament constituency)|Hartlepool]], losing to [[Peter Mandelson]].<ref name=\"polling\">[http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/guide/seat-profiles/sedgefield UKPollingReport: Sedgefield]</ref>\n\nSeveral other candidates contested the election. The [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP) selected [[Toby Horton]], who formerly contested the seat for the Conservatives in 1983, and in 1992 stood in [[Rother Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Rother Valley]]. The [[Green Party of England and Wales]] chose Chris Haine, and the [[British National Party]] chose Andrew Spence, who was involved in the 2000 [[UK fuel protests]] and stood for UKIP in the seat in 2001. The leader of the [[Official Monster Raving Loony Party]], [[Howling Laud Hope|Alan Hope]], also stood, having previously contested a long list of seats in both general and by-elections. The [[English Democrats]] chose Stephen Gash, and [[Operation Christian Vote]] fielded barrister Tim Grainger. [[Norman Scarth]] stood as an independent \"anti crime\" candidate, having previously contested [[Chesterfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Chesterfield]] in 1997 as an \"independent old age pensioner\".<ref name=\"polling\" /> Local [[independent (politician)|independent]] councillor Paul Gittins stood on a platform calling for the regeneration of the centre of [[Newton Aycliffe]].<ref>Greg Hurst, \"[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article2034131.ece Meet the man who would be Tony Blair]\", ''[[The Times]]''</ref>\n\n==Result==\nWilson held the seat for Labour with a majority reduced by over 11,000. The Liberal Democrats overtook the Conservatives for second place, with an 11% swing. The British National Party and independent local campaigner Paul Gittins both retained their deposits.<ref>\"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6907049.stm Labour holds on to Blair's seat]\", ''[[BBC News]]''</ref>\n\n{{Election box begin | title=[[Sedgefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Sedgefield]] by-election, 2007<ref name=\"Demon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.election.demon.co.uk/by2005.html|title=Results of Byelections in the 2005-2010 Parliament|last=Boothroyd|first=David|access-date=2015-10-05|website=United Kingdom Election Results}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Phil Wilson (British politician)|Phil Wilson]]\n  |votes      = 12,528\n  |percentage = 44.8\n  |change     = -14.1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n  |candidate  = Greg Stone\n  |votes      = 5,572\n  |percentage = 19.9\n  |change     = +8.0\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Graham Robb\n  |votes      = 4,082\n  |percentage = 14.6\n  |change     = +0.2\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party       = British National Party\n |candidate   = Andrew Spence\n |votes       = 2,494\n |percentage  = 8.9\n |change      = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Independent (politician)\n  |candidate  = Paul Gittins\n  |votes      = 1,885\n  |percentage = 6.7\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = UK Independence Party\n  |candidate  = Toby Horton\n  |votes      = 536\n  |percentage = 1.9\n  |change     = +0.3\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Green Party of England and Wales\n  |candidate  = Chris Haine\n  |votes      = 348\n  |percentage = 1.2\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = English Democrats Party\n  |candidate  = Stephen Gash\n  |votes      = 177\n  |percentage = 0.6\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Christian Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Tim Grainger\n  |votes      = 177\n  |percentage = 0.6\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Official Monster Raving Loony Party\n  |candidate  = [[Howling Laud Hope|Alan Hope]]\n  |votes      = 129\n  |percentage = 0.5\n  |change     = +0.1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate|\n  |party      = Anti Crime\n  |candidate  = [[Norman Scarth]]\n  |votes      = 34\n  |percentage = 0.1\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      = 6,956\n  |percentage = 24.9\n  |change     = -19.6\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      = 27,962\n  |percentage = 41.6\n  |change     = -20.6\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n |winner = Labour Party (UK)\n |swing = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==General Election 2005 result==\n{{Election box begin | title=[[2005 United Kingdom general election|General election 2005]]: [[Sedgefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Sedgefield]]}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Labour Party (UK)\n |candidate = [[Tony Blair]]\n |votes = 24,421\n |percentage = 58.9\n |change = -6.0\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Conservative Party (UK)\n |candidate = Gp Capt [[Al Lockwood]]\n |votes = 5,972\n |percentage = 14.4\n |change = -6.5\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n |candidate = Robert Browne\n |votes = 4,935\n |percentage = 11.9\n |change = +2.9\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Independent (politician)\n |candidate = [[Reg Keys]]\n |votes = 4,252\n |percentage = 10.3\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = UK Independence Party\n |candidate = William Brown\n |votes = 646\n |percentage = 1.6\n |change = -0.8\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = National Front (UK)\n |candidate = Mark Farrell\n |votes = 253\n |percentage = 0.6\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Veritas (political party)\n |candidate = Fiona Luckhurst-Matthews\n |votes = 218\n |percentage = 0.5\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Independent (politician)\n |candidate = Berony Abraham\n |votes = 205\n |percentage = 0.5\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Official Monster Raving Loony Party\n |candidate = Melodie Staniforth\n |votes = 157\n |percentage = 0.4\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate|\n |party = [[Blair Must Go Party]]\n |candidate = Jonathan Cockburn\n |votes = 103\n |percentage = 0.2\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate|\n |party = [[Senior Citizens Party]]\n |candidate = Terry Pattinson\n |votes = 97\n |percentage = 0.2\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate|\n |party = [[UK Pensioners Party]]\n |candidate = Cherri Gilham\n |votes = 82\n |percentage = 0.2\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Independent (politician)\n |candidate = [[Helen John]]\n |votes = 68\n |percentage = 0.2\n |change = -0.4\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Independent (politician)\n |candidate = John Barker\n |votes = 45\n |percentage = 0.1\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Independent (politician)\n |candidate = Julian Brennan\n |votes = 17\n |percentage = 0.0\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n |votes = 18,449\n |percentage = 44.5\n |change = \n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n |votes = 41,475\n |percentage = 62.2\n |change = +0.2\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n |winner = Labour Party (UK)\n |swing = 0.2\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6244358.stm BBC News]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070911222438/http://www.sedgefield-labour.com/ Labour's Sedgefield By-Election Website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070709052707/http://sedgefieldlibdems.org.uk/ Liberal Democrats Sedgefield By-Election Website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070901013630/http://www.sedgefieldconservatives.com/ Conservative Sedgefield By-Election Website]\n*[http://by_elections.blogspot.com/ By-Election blog]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070713070957/http://www.ukipsedgefield.org/ Sedgefield UK Independence Party]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110719102728/http://by-elections.co.uk/sedgefield07.html Election leaflets from the by-election campaign]\n\n{{By-elections to the 54th UK Parliament}}\n\n[[Category:2007 elections in the United Kingdom|Sedgefield by-election]]\n[[Category:2007 in England|Sedgefield by-election]]\n[[Category:By-elections to the Parliament of the United Kingdom in County Durham constituencies|Sedgefield]]\n[[Category:Sedgefield (borough)]]\n[[Category:2000s in County Durham]]\n[[Category:July 2007 events in the United Kingdom|Sedgefield by-election]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name = Sedgefield by-election\n| type = parliamentary\n| country = United Kingdom\n| seats_for_election = [[Sedgefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Sedgefield]] parliamentary seat\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 2005 United Kingdom general election\n| previous_year = 2005\n| next_election = 2010 United Kingdom general election\n| next_year = 2010\n| election_date = 19 July 2007\n\n| candidate1 = [[Phil Wilson (British politician)|Phil Wilson]]\n| image1 = [[File:Phil Wilson 2015.jpg|90px]]\n| party1 = Labour Party (UK)\n| popular_vote1 = '''12,528'''\n| percentage1 = '''44.8%'''\n| swing1         = {{decrease}}14.1%\n\n| candidate2 = Greg Stone\n| image2 = [[File:No image.svg|90px]]\n| party2 = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n| popular_vote2 = 5,572\n| percentage2 = 19.9%\n| swing2         = {{increase}}8.0%\n\n| candidate3 = Graham Robb\n| image3 = [[File:No image.svg|90px]]\n| party3 = Conservative Party (UK)\n| popular_vote3 = 4,082\n| percentage3 = 14.6%\n| swing3         = {{increase}}0.2%\n| candidate4 = Andrew Spence\n| image4 = [[File:No image wide.svg|95x50px|Blank]]\n| party4 = British National Party\n| popular_vote4 = 2,494\n| percentage4 = 8.9%\n| swing4        = ''New party''\n| candidate5 = Paul Gittins\n| image5 = [[File:No image wide.svg|95x50px|Blank]]\n| party5 = Independent (politician)\n| popular_vote5 = 1,885\n| percentage5 = 6.7%\n| swing5        = ''New party''\n| title = MP\n| posttitle = Subsequent MP\n| before_election = [[Tony Blair]]\n| before_party = Labour Party (UK)\n| after_election = [[Phil Wilson (British politician)|Phil Wilson]]\n| after_party = Labour Party (UK)\n}}\n\n[[Image:SedgefieldConstituency.svg|thumb|Map of Sedgefield]]\nThe '''Sedgefield by-election, 2007''' was a [[by-election]] held on 19 July 2007 for the [[British House of Commons]] constituency of [[Sedgefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Sedgefield]] in [[County Durham]].  The [[2007 Ealing Southall by-election|Ealing Southall by-election]] was also held on 19 July.\n\nThe by-election was triggered when [[Tony Blair]], the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for Sedgefield and former [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]], \"[[Resignation from the British House of Commons|resigned]]\" to become envoy for the international diplomatic [[Quartet on the Middle East]].  To resign as an MP, Blair accepted the office of [[Steward and Bailiff of the Three Hundreds of Chiltern]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/newsroom_and_speeches/press/2007/press_72_07.cfm |work=HM Treasury |title=Three Hundreds of Chiltern |date=2007-06-27 |accessdate=2007-06-27}}</ref> thereby deliberately disqualifying himself from Parliament and causing the by-election.  Blair had held the constituency since its creation for the [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983 election]], and Labour had held its predecessor constituencies since the [[1935 United Kingdom general election|1935 election]].\n\nAccording to [[Sedgefield]] Borough Council, the electorate for the by-election was 67,339 which represents an increase of 673 (1%) on the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]].\n\n==Candidates==\nThe [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] selected [[Phil Wilson (British politician)|Phil Wilson]], a [[public relations]] consultant, local party member and one of the \"Famous Five\" who had promoted [[Tony Blair]]'s first candidacy in 1983. He was chosen from a shortlist of five candidates, including former Minister [[Melanie Johnson]].<ref name=\"famous\">Chris Lloyd, \"[http://www.thisisthenortheast.co.uk/display.var.1518245.0.labour_chooses_one_of_the_famous_five.php Labour chooses one of the 'Famous Five']\", ''[[The Northern Echo]]''</ref> The [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] chose North East regeneration expert Greg Stone, a councillor in [[Newcastle-upon-Tyne]] and former candidate in the [[Vale of York (UK Parliament constituency)|Vale of York]] in the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 election]] and [[Newcastle-upon-Tyne Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle-upon-Tyne Central]] in the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 election]].<ref name=\"famous\"/> The Conservatives stood Graham Robb, a [[public relations]] consultant and former [[radio presenter]], who stood for the party in [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]] in [[Hartlepool (UK Parliament constituency)|Hartlepool]], losing to [[Peter Mandelson]].<ref name=\"polling\">[http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/guide/seat-profiles/sedgefield UKPollingReport: Sedgefield]</ref>\n\nSeveral other candidates contested the election. The [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP) selected [[Toby Horton]], who formerly contested the seat for the Conservatives in 1983, and in 1992 stood in [[Rother Valley (UK Parliament constituency)|Rother Valley]]. The [[Green Party of England and Wales]] chose Chris Haine, and the [[British National Party]] chose Andrew Spence, who was involved in the 2000 [[UK fuel protests]] and stood for UKIP in the seat in 2001. The leader of the [[Official Monster Raving Loony Party]], [[Howling Laud Hope|Alan Hope]], also stood, having previously contested a long list of seats in both general and by-elections. The [[English Democrats]] chose Stephen Gash, and [[Operation Christian Vote]] fielded barrister Tim Grainger. [[Norman Scarth]] stood as an independent \"anti crime\" candidate, having previously contested [[Chesterfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Chesterfield]] in 1997 as an \"independent old age pensioner\".<ref name=\"polling\" /> Local [[independent (politician)|independent]] councillor Paul Gittins stood on a platform calling for the regeneration of the centre of [[Newton Aycliffe]].<ref>Greg Hurst, \"[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article2034131.ece Meet the man who would be Tony Blair]\", ''[[The Times]]''</ref>\n\n==Result==\nWilson held the seat for Labour with a majority reduced by over 11,000. The Liberal Democrats overtook the Conservatives for second place, with an 11% swing. The British National Party and independent local campaigner Paul Gittins both retained their deposits.<ref>\"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6907049.stm Labour holds on to Blair's seat]\", ''[[BBC News]]''</ref>\n\n{{Election box begin | title=[[Sedgefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Sedgefield]] by-election, 2007<ref name=\"Demon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.election.demon.co.uk/by2005.html|title=Results of Byelections in the 2005-2010 Parliament|last=Boothroyd|first=David|access-date=2015-10-05|website=United Kingdom Election Results}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Phil Wilson (British politician)|Phil Wilson]]\n  |votes      = 12,528\n  |percentage = 44.8\n  |change     = -14.1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n  |candidate  = Greg Stone\n  |votes      = 5,572\n  |percentage = 19.9\n  |change     = +8.0\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Graham Robb\n  |votes      = 4,082\n  |percentage = 14.6\n  |change     = +0.2\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party       = British National Party\n |candidate   = Andrew Spence\n |votes       = 2,494\n |percentage  = 8.9\n |change      = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Independent (politician)\n  |candidate  = Paul Gittins\n  |votes      = 1,885\n  |percentage = 6.7\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = UK Independence Party\n  |candidate  = Toby Horton\n  |votes      = 536\n  |percentage = 1.9\n  |change     = +0.3\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Green Party of England and Wales\n  |candidate  = Chris Haine\n  |votes      = 348\n  |percentage = 1.2\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = English Democrats Party\n  |candidate  = Stephen Gash\n  |votes      = 177\n  |percentage = 0.6\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Christian Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Tim Grainger\n  |votes      = 177\n  |percentage = 0.6\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Official Monster Raving Loony Party\n  |candidate  = [[Howling Laud Hope|Alan Hope]]\n  |votes      = 129\n  |percentage = 0.5\n  |change     = +0.1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate|\n  |party      = Anti Crime\n  |candidate  = [[Norman Scarth]]\n  |votes      = 34\n  |percentage = 0.1\n  |change     = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      = 6,956\n  |percentage = 24.9\n  |change     = -19.6\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      = 27,962\n  |percentage = 41.6\n  |change     = -20.6\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n |winner = Labour Party (UK)\n |swing = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==General Election 2005 result==\n{{Election box begin | title=[[2005 United Kingdom general election|General election 2005]]: [[Sedgefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Sedgefield]]}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Labour Party (UK)\n |candidate = [[Tony Blair]]\n |votes = 24,421\n |percentage = 58.9\n |change = -6.0\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Conservative Party (UK)\n |candidate = Gp Capt [[Al Lockwood]]\n |votes = 5,972\n |percentage = 14.4\n |change = -6.5\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n |candidate = Robert Browne\n |votes = 4,935\n |percentage = 11.9\n |change = +2.9\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Independent (politician)\n |candidate = [[Reg Keys]]\n |votes = 4,252\n |percentage = 10.3\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = UK Independence Party\n |candidate = William Brown\n |votes = 646\n |percentage = 1.6\n |change = -0.8\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = National Front (UK)\n |candidate = Mark Farrell\n |votes = 253\n |percentage = 0.6\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Veritas (political party)\n |candidate = Fiona Luckhurst-Matthews\n |votes = 218\n |percentage = 0.5\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Independent (politician)\n |candidate = Berony Abraham\n |votes = 205\n |percentage = 0.5\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Official Monster Raving Loony Party\n |candidate = Melodie Staniforth\n |votes = 157\n |percentage = 0.4\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate|\n |party = [[Blair Must Go Party]]\n |candidate = Jonathan Cockburn\n |votes = 103\n |percentage = 0.2\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate|\n |party = [[Senior Citizens Party]]\n |candidate = Terry Pattinson\n |votes = 97\n |percentage = 0.2\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate|\n |party = [[UK Pensioners Party]]\n |candidate = Cherri Gilham\n |votes = 82\n |percentage = 0.2\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Independent (politician)\n |candidate = [[Helen John]]\n |votes = 68\n |percentage = 0.2\n |change = -0.4\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Independent (politician)\n |candidate = John Barker\n |votes = 45\n |percentage = 0.1\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n |party = Independent (politician)\n |candidate = Julian Brennan\n |votes = 17\n |percentage = 0.0\n |change = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n |votes = 18,449\n |percentage = 44.5\n |change = \n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n |votes = 41,475\n |percentage = 62.2\n |change = +0.2\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n |winner = Labour Party (UK)\n |swing = 0.2\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6244358.stm BBC News]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070911222438/http://www.sedgefield-labour.com/ Labour's Sedgefield By-Election Website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070709052707/http://sedgefieldlibdems.org.uk/ Liberal Democrats Sedgefield By-Election Website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070901013630/http://www.sedgefieldconservatives.com/ Conservative Sedgefield By-Election Website]\n*[http://by_elections.blogspot.com/ By-Election blog]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070713070957/http://www.ukipsedgefield.org/ Sedgefield UK Independence Party]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110719102728/http://by-elections.co.uk/sedgefield07.html Election leaflets from the by-election campaign]\n\n{{By-elections to the 54th UK Parliament}}\n\n[[Category:2007 elections in the United Kingdom|Sedgefield by-election]]\n[[Category:2007 in England|Sedgefield by-election]]\n[[Category:By-elections to the Parliament of the United Kingdom in County Durham constituencies]]\n[[Category:Sedgefield (borough)]]\n[[Category:2000s in County Durham]]\n[[Category:July 2007 events in the United Kingdom|Sedgefield by-election]]\n", "name_user": "MSGJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "+sortkey", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2007_Sedgefield_by-election"}
{"title_page": "An Unbelievable Story of Rape", "text_new": "\"'''An Unbelievable Story of Rape'''\" is a 2015 article about a [[Washington and Colorado serial rape cases|series of rapes]] in the U.S. states of [[Washington (state)|Washington]] and [[Colorado]] that occurred between 2008 and 2011, and the subsequent police investigations. It was a collaboration between two American, non-profit news organizations, [[The Marshall Project]] and [[ProPublica]]. The article was written by [[Ken Armstrong (journalist)|Ken Armstrong]] and [[T. Christian Miller]]. It won the 2016 [[Pulitzer Prize for Explanatory Reporting]] and the 2015 [[George Polk Award]] for Justice Reporting.\n\nThe article alternates between two true stories of events occurring between August 2008 and June 2012. The first narrative is about a woman in [[Lynnwood, Washington]], known pseudonymously as \"Marie\", who reports being raped to the police. After repeated interrogation by the police, who do not believe her, she says that her report was false. She is subsequently charged with a [[gross misdemeanor]] for false accusation. The second narrative details the police investigations into a serial rapist in Colorado, who is known to have raped four women and made a fifth attempt. The man is arrested in February 2011, and subsequent evidence on his hard drive reveals that Marie, not previously known to the local investigative team, was raped by him.\n\nT. Christian Miller of ProPublica had been reporting on law enforcement failures in identifying rapists throughout 2015. In August, he learned of the case of Marie and contacted her lawyer, discovering that Ken Armstrong of The Marshall Project was already working on a similar story. They began to collaborate, with Armstrong writing about Marie's story in Washington and Miller writing about the police investigation in Colorado. Marie agreed to speak to Armstrong after six months of communication. The article was further informed by other interviews and thousands of pages of public records material.\n\nThe article was later adapted into the Netflix series ''[[Unbelievable (miniseries)|Unbelievable]]'', which has received critical acclaim. The article also provided the basis of Miller and Armstrong's full-length book ''A False Report: A True Story of Rape in America'' (2018).\n\n==Article content==\nIn [[Lynnwood, Washington]], an 18-year-old woman, referred to as \"Marie,\" reported being bound, gagged and raped at knifepoint to police. Following police confrontation about inconsistencies in her story, she said that she made the incident up. In March 2009, she was charged with a [[gross misdemeanor]], fined $500 and put on probation. Marie had been sexually and physically abused in early life and was in foster care for most of her childhood. She joined Project Ladder at age 18, a program designed for people transitioning from foster care to living alone.\n\nIn [[Golden, Colorado]] during January 2011, Detective Stacy Galbraith interviewed a woman who was raped at gunpoint for four hours. When Galbraith talked to her husband, he observed familiarity with an incident reported to his police department in Westminster. Galbraith began collaboration with Westminster Detective Edna Hendershot, who had investigated two cases in which women aged 59 and 65 were raped in similar ways. They also discovered a burglary where a masked man had attempted to tie up a 46-year-old woman, who jumped out of her window and was badly injured. The four known cases took place in different suburbs of [[Denver]]. The man had gone to extreme lengths to avoid leaving DNA evidence, but [[touch DNA]] from the same paternal family line was found at three scenes.\n\nMarie had made her report in August 2008 to Sergeant Jeffrey Mason and Jerry Rittgarn. Police guidelines advised that rape victims should not be interrogated, as they may be uncertain of details or report conflicting information. Investigating Marie's report, police found evidence of an assailant and abrasions to Marie's vagina and wrist. However, two of Marie's former foster parents began to disbelieve her due to her seemingly calm demeanour, one reporting doubts to the police. Following this, and Marie's conflicting account of when she phoned a friend, Mason and Rittgarn made Marie repeat her story, Rittgarn saying that he disbelieved her. He asked if the rapist was real and she said \"no.\" Without reading the [[Miranda warning|''Miranda'' warning]], they asked her to write that she had made a false report. She wrote instead that she had dreamed the incident, now unsure of what happened. After hours of further questioning, Marie wrote that she had been lying.\n\nProject Ladder staff made Marie return to police when she said she made the report under [[duress]]. She asked to take a [[polygraph test]]\u2014though such tests do not provide reliable evidence\u2014but declined when Rittgarn threatened jail and loss of housing if she failed it. Mason filed a false reporting charge; such charges in similar circumstances were rare. Marie became the subject of media reports and an attack website. She quit her [[Costco]] job and considered suicide. In October 2008, one of Marie's foster parents saw a report of a woman in [[Kirkland, Washington]] raped in the same way as Marie. Kirkland police abandoned this lead after Lynnwood police told them at least twice that Marie's account was a lie.\n\nIn February 2011, a report was unearthed of a suspicious vehicle registered to army veteran Marc Patrick O'Leary, whose description matched the attacker. FBI agents collected DNA evidence from his brother which showed one of them was the rapist. A search warrant led to the arrest of O'Leary. He possessed a mask, gun, women's underwear and other identifying evidence. Photographs of Marie were found on O'Leary's hard drive. O'Leary had watched women for hundreds of hours, breaking into their houses multiple times before each rape. In December 2011, O'Leary was sentenced to 327.5 years in prison for four incidents in Colorado. In June 2012, he was sentenced to an additional 38.5 years for two incidents in Washington.\n\nAn external report condemned the handling of Marie's case. It described the officers' behaviour as \"bullying\" and highlighted threats of jail and housing assistance removal as \"coercive, cruel, and unbelievably unprofessional.\" An internal review also concluded that Mason and Rittgarn's behaviour was \"designed to elicit a confession of false reporting.\" In 2015, the commander of Lynnwood's Criminal Investigations Division said that practices had since changed. Neither Mason nor Rittgarn were disciplined. After Marie approached Mason, he offered an apology. Marie sued the city, winning $150,000. By the time of the article, Marie was married with two children.<ref name=\"Unbelievable Marshall\"/><ref name=\"Unbelievable ProPublica\"/>\n\n==Background==\n===History===\n\"An Unbelievable Story of Rape\" was written by [[Ken Armstrong (journalist)|Ken Armstrong]] and [[T. Christian Miller]]. A collaboration between [[The Marshall Project]] and [[ProPublica]], it was published on both websites on December 16, 2015.<ref name=\"Unbelievable Marshall\">{{cite web|url=https://www.themarshallproject.org/2015/12/16/an-unbelievable-story-of-rape|title=An Unbelievable Story of Rape|publisher=[[The Marshall Project]]|last1=Armstrong|first1=Ken|last2=Miller|first2=T. Christian|date=December 16, 2015|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Unbelievable ProPublica\">{{cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/false-rape-accusations-an-unbelievable-story|title=An Unbelievable Story of Rape|publisher=[[ProPublica]]|last1=Armstrong|first1=Ken|last2=Miller|first2=T. Christian|date=December 16, 2015|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref> Colorado publication ''[[Westword]]'' reprinted the article as their cover story on May 19, 2016.<ref name=\"Westword\"/> The Marshall Project and ProPublica are American non-profit online news organizations. The Marshall Project specializes in criminal justice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/17/business/media/marshall-project-kicks-off-with-look-at-legal-delays.html?_r=0|title = Marshall Project Kicks Off With Look at Legal Delays|date = November 16, 2014|accessdate = September 24, 2019|work=[[The New York Times]]|last=Somaiya|first=Ravi}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/cifamerica/2010/apr/13/pulitzer-prize-non-profit-news|title=Pulitzer progress for non-profit news|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Kennedy|first=Dan|date=April 13, 2010|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nT. Christian Miller was a senior reporter at ProPublica. Throughout 2015, he had been reporting on the failure of law enforcement to trace rapists, including the case of [[Darren Sharper]], a football player who raped nine women. Miller had discovered that an FBI database to identify serial murderers and rapists was mostly unused in the cases of rape, as most police departments fail to upload sexual assault reports.<ref name=\"about that\"/> His article \"The FBI Built a Database That Can Catch Rapists \u2014 Almost Nobody Uses It\" was published in July 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/the-fbi-built-a-database-that-can-catch-rapists-almost-nobody-uses-it|title=The FBI Built a Database That Can Catch Rapists \u2014 Almost Nobody Uses It|publisher=[[ProPublica]]|last=Miller|first=T. Christian|date=July 30, 2015|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy August 2015, Miller was working on a report about the [[Washington and Colorado serial rape cases]], with focus on the woman who recanted a report of rape after intense police interrogation, proven true years later by the rapist's conviction\u2014known in the article by her middle name \"Marie\".<ref name=\"about that\"/><ref name=\"how we reported\"/> Miller called the woman's lawyer and discovered she was in contact with Ken Armstrong of The Marshall Project, who had been working on an article about the case for several months.<ref name=\"about that\">{{cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/about-propublica-marshall-project-rape-story-collaboration|title=About That Unbelievable Story|publisher=[[ProPublica]]|last=Engelberg|first=Stephen|date=December 24, 2015|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref> The teams decided to collaborate.<ref name=\"Nieman\"/>\n\n===Research and writing===\nArmstrong's editor Joe Sexton and Miller's editor [[Bill Keller]] had worked together at ''[[The New York Times]]''. Numerous other editors contributed to the article, including managing editor Kirsten Danis of The Marshall Project.<ref name=\"Nieman\"/> As the two reporters and two primary editors were all male, the team ensured that they consulted women's input, particularly in regards to how graphic or detailed to make the description of Marie's rape.<ref name=\"Nieman\"/><ref name=\"Poynter\"/>\n\nMiller wrote the sections about the woman in Colorado, whilst Armstrong wrote the sections about the investigation in Washington. The sections are ordered alternately, with an opening paragraph about the woman in Washington being charged with false reporting.<ref name=\"Poynter\">{{cite web|url=https://www.poynter.org/reporting-editing/2016/coaches-corner-the-story-behind-an-unbelievable-story-of-rape/|title=Coaches' Corner: The story behind 'An Unbelievable Story of Rape'|publisher=[[Poynter Institute]]|last=Wilmsen|first=Steve|date=January 12, 2016|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref> The structure was proposed by Sexton. The first draft was 15,000 words in length,<ref name=\"Nieman\"/> shortened to 12,000 in the final version.<ref name=\"NYT Polk\"/> Keller and other editors recommended cutting down on the ending of the article, yielding a short epilogue.<ref name=\"Nieman\"/>\n\nAfter seven months of email and phone communication with Marie's lawyer, Marie agreed to speak to Armstrong. It was the first time she had agreed to be interviewed by a journalist.<ref name=\"Westword\"/><ref name=\"Nieman\"/> Armstrong and Miller also interviewed two of Marie's foster parents and her friend, her public defender and civil suit attorney. The pair spoke to various police officers, including Detectives Stacy Galbraith and Edna Hendershot who investigated the Colorado cases.<ref name=\"how we reported\"/> Three officers in the Lynnwood Police Department were interviewed, including Mason, one of the officers who handled Marie's request. The interviews were made late in the process, the department having refused earlier requests for comment.<ref name=\"Nieman\"/> The other officer, Rittgarn, declined to be interviewed. Serial rapist Marc O'Leary was also interviewed.<ref name=\"how we reported\">{{cite web|url=https://www.themarshallproject.org/2015/12/16/how-we-reported-an-unbelievable-story-of-rape|title=How We Reported 'An Unbelievable Story of Rape'|publisher=[[The Marshall Project]]|last=Armstrong|first=Ken|last2=Miller|first2=T. Christian|date=December 16, 2015|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref> A brief audio recording of Marie describing her rape is included in the article.<ref name=\"Unbelievable ProPublica\"/>\n\nFor the article, Armstrong and Miller made [[public records request]]s to police departments and prosecuting attorney's offices in Washington and Colorado. They received thousands of pages of documents, including investigative reports, case reviews, crime scene photographs and footage of surveillance and O'Leary after his arrest. News coverage, criminal justice guidelines and court transcripts were also consulted.<ref name=\"how we reported\"/> Extracts of an external report made of the police department that investigated Marie's case were made public for the first time in the article.<ref name=\"Unbelievable Marshall\"/>\n\n==Response==\nThe article won the 2015 [[George Polk Award]] for Justice Reporting, presented by [[Long Island University]], and the 2016 Al Nakkula Award for Police Reporting, awarded by the [[University of Colorado Boulder]] and [[Denver Press Club]].<ref name=\"UofC\"/><ref name=\"NYT Polk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/15/nyregion/new-york-times-investigation-of-navy-seals-among-winners-of-2015-polk-awards.html|title=New York Times Journalists Among Winners of 2015 Polk Awards|work=[[The New York Times]]|last=Barron|first=James|date=February 14, 2016|accessdate=September 24, 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref> It also won the 2016 [[Pulitzer Prize for Explanatory Reporting]], the article being described as \"a startling examination and expos\u00e9 of law enforcement's enduring failures to investigate reports of rape properly and to comprehend the traumatic effects on its victims\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulitzer.org/prize-winners-by-category/207|title=Explanatory Reporting|publisher=Pulitzer Prize Board|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulitzer.org/winners/t-christian-miller-propublica-and-ken-armstrong-marshall-project|title=T. Christian Miller of ProPublica and Ken Armstrong of The Marshall Project|publisher=Pulitzer Prize Board|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> It was a finalist in the 2016 [[National Magazine Awards]] in the Feature Writing category.<ref name=\"Nieman\">{{cite web|url=https://nieman.harvard.edu/stories/notable-narrative-ken-armstrong-t-christian-miller-and-an-unbelievable-story-of-rape/|title=Notable Narrative: Ken Armstrong, T. Christian Miller and \"An Unbelievable Story of Rape\"|publisher=[[Nieman Foundation for Journalism]]|last=Fitzgerald|first=Michael|date=January 26, 2016|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nRusty Foster of ''[[Fast Company]]'' described the article as \"impeccably reported and written, and completely devastating\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3054755/today-in-tabs-look-at-these-rich-idiots-suffering-on-mars|title=Today in Tabs: Look At These Rich Idiots Suffering On Mars|work=[[Fast Company]]|last=Foster|first=Rusty|date=December 16, 2015}}</ref> Nora Caplan-Bricker of ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' reflected that \"Marie's story helps remind us that false reports of rape are the exception, not the rule\", believing that the article shows the \"ruinous consequences\" and \"ubiquity\" of rape victims being disbelieved.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/human-interest/2015/12/rape-victim-who-recanted-story-is-vindicated.html|title=A Haunting Story That Shows the Consequences\u2014and the Ubiquity\u2014of Doubting Rape Victims|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|last=Caplan-Bricker|first=Nora|date=December 16, 2015|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Writing for the alternative Wisconsin newspaper ''[[Isthmus (newspaper)|Isthmus]]'', Bill Lueders praised the article and compared it to his own reporting about a similar case from 1997 to 2001, where a woman was charged by police after ostensibly making a false report of rape, but was later proven truthful by DNA evidence leading to her rapist's conviction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://isthmus.com/news/news/national-rape-story-has-madison-parallels/|title=National rape story has Madison parallels|work=[[Isthmus (newspaper)|Isthmus]]|last=Lueders|first=Bill|date=December 21, 2015|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe University of Colorado Boulder reported in 2016 that law enforcement officials had requested to use the article in training. Jennifer Gentile Long, CEO of AEquitas: The Prosecutors' Resource on Violence Against Women, commented that the article presented an \"extraordinary learning opportunity for both criminal justice professionals and ordinary citizens alike\".<ref name=\"UofC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.colorado.edu/today/2016/04/15/team-wins-al-nakkula-award-police-reporting|title=Team wins Al Nakkula Award for Police Reporting|publisher=[[University of Colorado Boulder]]|last=Lock|first=Elizabeth|date=April 15, 2016|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref> Journalist [[Pamela Colloff]] referenced the article as an example of good reporting on criminal justice, as it is told from the perspective of a survivor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nieman.harvard.edu/stories/covering-failures-in-the-justice-system-with-patience-for-facts-and-sensitivity-to-victims/|title=Covering failures in the justice system with patience for facts and sensitivity to victims|publisher=[[Nieman Foundation for Journalism]]|last=Tarrant|first=David|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Subsequent media==\n\"An Unbelievable Story of Rape\" was published on December 16, 2015. In the days following, Miller and Armstrong published two subsequent articles: \"A Brutal Crime, Often Terribly Investigated\" enumerated five recommendations for police institutions to improve their handling of rape cases, while \"Rape is Rape, Isn't It?\" commented on the changing definition of rape used by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themarshallproject.org/2015/12/18/a-brutal-crime-often-terribly-investigated|title=A Brutal Crime, Often Terribly Investigated|publisher=[[The Marshall Project]]|last=Armstrong|first=Ken|last2=Miller|first2=T. Christian|date=December 18, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/flawed-rape-statistics-hamper-understanding-and-preventing-the-crime|title=Rape is Rape, Isn't It?|publisher=[[ProPublica]]|last=Armstrong|first=Ken|last2=Miller|first2=T. Christian|date=December 18, 2015|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{external media\n|audio1 = [https://longform.org/posts/longform-podcast-201-t-christian-miller-and-ken-armstrong ''#201: T. Christian Miller and Ken Armstrong'']<br>Episode of ''Longform''.\n|audio2 = [https://www.thisamericanlife.org/581/anatomy-of-doubt ''An Anatomy of Doubt'']<br>Episode of ''[[This American Life]]''.\n|audio3 = [https://www.upr.org/post/revisiting-pulitzer-prize-winning-journalist-ken-armstrong-tuesdays-access-utah ''Revisiting Pulitzer Prize-Winning Journalist Ken Armstrong On Tuesday's Access Utah'']<br>Episode of ''Access Utah''.\n}}\n\nIn December 2015, ProPublica published a podcast episode where Miller and Armstrong discussed the article.<ref>{{cite podcast |host=Cynthia Gordy Giwa |title=How Almost Getting Scooped Brought Two Competing Reporters Together |publisher=[[ProPublica]] |date=December 24, 2015 |url=https://www.propublica.org/podcast/how-almost-getting-scooped-brought-two-competing-reporters-together/ |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> At the [[Investigative Reporters and Editors]]' 2016 conference, the pair gave a talk about their experience writing the article.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ire.org/events-and-training/event/2199/2570/|title=Constructing the narrative: An unbelievable story of rape|publisher=[[Investigative Reporters and Editors]]|last1=Armstrong|first=Ken|last2=Miller|first2=T. Christian|date=June 17, 2016|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> In July 2016, they appeared on the ''Longform'' podcast to discuss the article.<ref name=\"Westword\">{{cite web|url=https://www.westword.com/news/the-backstory-of-how-the-pulitzer-winning-unbelievable-story-of-rape-came-to-be-8134322|title=The Backstory of How the Pulitzer-Winning \"Unbelievable Story of Rape\" Came to Be|work=[[Westword]]|last=Walker|first=Chris|date=July 26, 2016|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref> Armstrong appeared on [[Utah Public Radio]] in November 2016, discussing the article on ''Access Utah''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.upr.org/post/revisiting-pulitzer-prize-winning-journalist-ken-armstrong-tuesdays-access-utah|title=Revisiting Pulitzer Prize-Winning Journalist Ken Armstrong On Tuesday's Access Utah|publisher=[[Utah Public Radio]]|last=Williams|first=Tom|date=November 22, 2016|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==={{anchor|Anatomy of Doubt}} ''An Anatomy of Doubt''===\n'''''An Anatomy of Doubt''''' is the 581st episode of the American radio program and podcast ''[[This American Life]]''. It adapts \"An Unbelievable Story of Rape\". Credited as a collaboration with The Marshall Project and ProPublica, it debuted on February 26, 2016. The hour-long episode features [[Ira Glass]], Ken Armstrong and [[Robyn Semien]] and includes interviews with Marie, Mason and two of Marie's foster parents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisamericanlife.org/581/anatomy-of-doubt|title=Anatomy of Doubt|work=[[This American Life]]|date=February 26, 2016|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themarshallproject.org/2016/02/25/this-american-life-unbelievable-story-rape|title=Listen to Our First Collaboration with \"This American Life\"|publisher=[[The Marshall Project]]|date=February 25, 2016|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Westword\"/>\n\n==={{anchor|A False Report: A True Story of Rape in America}} ''A False Report''===\n<!-- Could be expanded into an article, for which see also: reviews on Crown Publishing page; https://www.npr.org/2018/02/06/583778370/a-false-report-highlights-how-women-who-report-sexual-assault-are-treated -->\nArmstrong and Miller adapted their article and additional research into a 304-page book, '''''A False Report: A True Story of Rape in America'''''. It was published on February 6, 2018 by the [[Crown Publishing Group]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crownpublishing.com/archives/news/false-report-true-story-rape-america|title=A False Report: A True Story of Rape in America By T. Christian Miller and Ken Armstrong|publisher=[[Crown Publishing Group]]|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themarysue.com/false-report-believe-women/|title=''A False Report'' Reminds Us of What Happens When You Don't Believe Women|work=[[The Mary Sue]]|author=Princess Weekes|date=January 19, 2018|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref> The book expands upon details of the case like O'Leary's perspective and subjects such as [[victim blaming]] and [[social media]] harassment.<ref name=\"IT False Report\"/><ref name=\"ST False Report\"/> Mason was interviewed for the book, but Rittgarn refused to speak to the authors without being paid.<ref name=\"ST False Report\">{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/books/a-false-report-looks-at-a-local-story-of-rape-and-its-aftermath/|title='A False Report' looks at a local story of rape and its aftermath|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|last=Rowe|first=Claudia|date=February 3, 2018|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe book received mostly positive critical reviews,<!-- Star Tribune, NYT, Seattle Times mostly positive; Irish Times mostly negative --> with Hamilton Cain of ''[[Star Tribune]]'' calling it an \"instant true-crime classic\".<ref name=\"Star\">{{cite web|url=https://www.startribune.com/review-a-false-report-a-true-story-of-rape-in-america-by-t-christian-miller-and-ken-armstrong/474226823/|title=Review: 'A False Report: A True Story of Rape in America,' by T. Christian Miller and Ken Armstrong|work=[[Star Tribune]]|last=Cain|first=Hamilton|date=February 16, 2018|accessdate=April 12, 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Emily Bazelon of ''[[The New York Times]]'' praised that the authors \"tell their story plainly, expertly and well\",<ref name=\"NYT False Report\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/06/books/review/a-false-report-t-christian-miller-ken-armstrong.html|title=The Lesson Here Is Listen to the Victim|work=[[The New York Times]]|last=Bazelon|first=Emily|date=March 6, 2018|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> and the style of alternating between Marie's story and the other Denver sexual assaults was praised by Claudie Rowe of ''[[The Seattle Times]]'' and Cain.<ref name=\"ST False Report\"/><ref name=\"Star\"/> However, though Rosita Boland of ''[[The Irish Times]]'' enjoyed the early sections of the book, she found it to have a \"curiously flat style overall, without any distinctive voice\".<ref name=\"IT False Report\">{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/a-false-report-review-a-powerful-story-about-a-serial-rapist-that-falls-flat-1.3388458|title=A False Report review: a powerful story about a serial rapist that falls flat|work=[[The Irish Times]]|last=Boland|first=Rosita|date=February 17, 2018|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===''Unbelievable''===\n{{main|Unbelievable (miniseries)}}\nThe [[Netflix]] miniseries ''Unbelievable'' is an eight-part adaptation of \"An Unbelievable Story of Rape\", also drawing from ''An Anatomy of Doubt'' and ''A False Report''. It premiered on September 13, 2019. The main characters are based on Marie Adler ([[Kaitlyn Dever]]) and Detectives Edna Hendershot and Stacy Galbraith, who were renamed as Grace Rasmussen ([[Toni Collette]]) and Karen Duvall ([[Merritt Wever]]). Marie, Armstrong and Miller were consulted during the production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/09/17/unbelievable-true-story-behind-netflixs-gripping-new-drama-about-women-who-solved-serial-rape-case/|title=The true story behind 'Unbelievable,' Netflix's gripping new drama about the women who solved a serial rape case|work=[[The Washington Post]]|last=Butler|first=Bethonie|date=September 17, 2019|accessdate=September 25, 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/unbelievable-trailer-sexual-assault-toni-colette-netflix-1202158956/ |title='Unbelievable' Trailer: Sexual Assault Victim Fights to Be Heard in Toni Colette-Starring Netflix Drama |last=Zilko |first=Christian |date=July 18, 2019 |website=IndieWire |access-date=July 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/how-a-pulitzer-prize-winning-investigation-became-netflixs-unbelievable-1239342|title=How a Pulitzer Prize-Winning Investigation Became Netflix's 'Unbelievable'|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last=Kilkenny|first=Katie|date=September 13, 2019|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNetflix reported that \"Unbelievable\" had been garnered 32 million views by the end of September, where a \"view\" entailed watching at least 70% of an episode. This made it the seventh-most viewed television series on the platform from August 2018 to September 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/tv-radio-web/netflix-has-revealed-its-most-watched-content-you-might-be-surprised-1.4060255|title=Netflix has revealed its most-watched content. You might be surprised|work=[[The Irish Times]]|last=Lee|first=Benjamin|date=October 23, 2019|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The program was nominated for numerous awards, including four nominations each at the [[Golden Globe Awards]] and the [[Critics' Choice Television Awards]], with one win at the latter.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2020-golden-globes-nominations-full-list-1259626 |title=Golden Globes: Full List of Nominations |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=December 9, 2019 |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://tvline.com/2019/12/08/critics-choice-awards-nominations-2020-full-list-tv-nominees/ |title=Critics' Choice Awards 2020: Fleabag, Watchmen, When They See Us, Unbelievable Among TV Nominees |website=[[TVLine]] |date=December 8, 2019 |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/critics-choice-awards-2020-winners-list-1202828353/|title=Critics' Choice Awards: 'Once Upon A Time In Hollywood' Wins Best Picture, Netflix And HBO Among Top Honorees \u2013 Full Winners List|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=Ramos|first=Dino-Ray|last2=Boucher|first2=Geoff|date=January 12, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the series has a rating of 98%, based on 82 reviews, with the summary: \"Heartbreaking and powerful, ''Unbelievable'' transcends familiar true-crime beats by shifting its gaze to survivors of abuse, telling their stories with grace and gravity.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/unbelievable/s01|title=Unbelievable: Season 1 (2019)|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the program has a rating of 83 out of 100 based on 25 reviews, indicating universal acclaim.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/unbelievable|title=Unbelievable|publisher=[[CBS]]|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2015 works]]\n[[Category:George Polk Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Investigative journalism]]\n[[Category:Pulitzer Prize for Investigative Reporting winners]]\n[[Category:Works about rape]]\n[[Category:Works about police officers]]\n[[Category:Works about American law enforcement agencies]]\n", "text_old": "\"'''An Unbelievable Story of Rape'''\" is a 2015 article about a [[Washington and Colorado serial rape cases|series of rapes]] in the U.S. states of [[Washington (state)|Washington]] and [[Colorado]] that occurred between 2008 and 2011, and the subsequent police investigations. It was a collaboration between two American, non-profit news organizations, [[The Marshall Project]] and [[ProPublica]]. The article was written by [[Ken Armstrong (journalist)|Ken Armstrong]] and [[T. Christian Miller]]. It won the 2016 [[Pulitzer Prize for Explanatory Reporting]] and the 2015 [[George Polk Award]] for Justice Reporting.\n\nThe article alternates between two true stories of events occurring between August 2008 and June 2012. The first narrative is about a woman in [[Lynnwood, Washington]], known pseudonymously as \"Marie\", who reports being raped to the police. After repeated interrogation by the police, who do not believe her, she says that her report was false. She is subsequently charged with a [[gross misdemeanor]] for false accusation. The second narrative details the police investigations into a serial rapist in Colorado, who is known to have raped four women and made a fifth attempt. The man is arrested in February 2011, and subsequent evidence on his hard drive reveals that Marie, not previously known to the local investigative team, was raped by him.\n\nT. Christian Miller of ProPublica had been reporting on law enforcement failures in identifying rapists throughout 2015. In August, he learned of the case of Marie and contacted her lawyer, discovering that Ken Armstrong of The Marshall Project was already working on a similar story. They began to collaborate, with Armstrong writing about Marie's story in Washington and Miller writing about the police investigation in Colorado. Marie agreed to speak to Armstrong after six months of communication. The article was further informed by other interviews and thousands of pages of public records material.\n\nThe article was later adapted into the Netflix series ''[[Unbelievable (miniseries)|Unbelievable]]'', which has received critical acclaim. The article also provided the basis of Miller and Armstrong's full-length book ''A False Report: A True Story of Rape in America'' (2018).\n\n==Article content==\nIn [[Lynnwood, Washington]], an 18-year-old woman, referred to as \"Marie,\" reported being bound, gagged and raped at knifepoint to police. Following police confrontation about inconsistencies in her story, she said that she made the incident up. In March 2009, she was charged with a [[gross misdemeanor]], fined $500 and put on probation. Marie had been sexually and physically abused in early life and was in foster care for most of her childhood. She joined Project Ladder at age 18, a program designed for people transitioning from foster care to living alone.\n\nIn [[Golden, Colorado]] during January 2011, Detective Stacy Galbraith interviewed a woman who was raped at gunpoint for four hours. When Galbraith talked to her husband, he observed familiarity with an incident reported to his police department in Westminster. Galbraith began collaboration with Westminster Detective Edna Hendershot, who had investigated two cases in which women aged 59 and 65 were raped in similar ways. They also discovered a burglary where a masked man had attempted to tie up a 46-year-old woman, who jumped out of her window and was badly injured. The four known cases took place in different suburbs of [[Denver]]. The man had gone to extreme lengths to avoid leaving DNA evidence, but [[touch DNA]] from the same paternal family line was found at three scenes.\n\nMarie had made her report in August 2008 to Sergeant Jeffrey Mason and Jerry Rittgarn. Police guidelines advised that rape victims should not be interrogated, as they may be uncertain of details or report conflicting information. Investigating Marie's report, police found evidence of an assailant and abrasions to Marie's vagina and wrist. However, two of Marie's former foster parents began to disbelieve her due to her seemingly calm demeanour, one reporting doubts to the police. Following this, and Marie's conflicting account of when she phoned a friend, Mason and Rittgarn made Marie repeat her story, Rittgarn saying that he disbelieved her. He asked if the rapist was real and she said \"no.\" Without reading the [[Miranda warning|''Miranda'' warning]], they asked her to write that she had made a false report. She wrote instead that she had dreamed the incident, now unsure of what happened. After hours of further questioning, Marie wrote that she had been lying.\n\nProject Ladder staff made Marie return to police when she said she made the report under [[duress]]. She asked to take a [[polygraph test]]\u2014though such tests do not provide reliable evidence\u2014but declined when Rittgarn threatened jail and loss of housing if she failed it. Mason filed a false reporting charge; such charges in similar circumstances were rare. Marie became the subject of media reports and an attack website. She quit her [[Costco]] job and considered suicide. In October 2008, one of Marie's foster parents saw a report of a woman in [[Kirkland, Washington]] raped in the same way as Marie. Kirkland police abandoned this lead after Lynnwood police told them at least twice that Marie's account was a lie.\n\nIn February 2011, a report was unearthed of a suspicious vehicle registered to army veteran Marc Patrick O'Leary, whose description matched the attacker. FBI agents collected DNA evidence from his brother which showed one of them was the rapist. A search warrant led to the arrest of O'Leary. He possessed a mask, gun, women's underwear and other identifying evidence. Photographs of Marie were found on O'Leary's hard drive. O'Leary had watched women for hundreds of hours, breaking into their houses multiple times before each rape. In December 2011, O'Leary was sentenced to 327.5 years in prison for four incidents in Colorado. In June 2012, he was sentenced to an additional 38.5 years for two incidents in Washington.\n\nAn external report condemned the handling of Marie's case. It described the officers' behaviour as \"bullying\" and highlighted threats of jail and housing assistance removal as \"coercive, cruel, and unbelievably unprofessional.\" An internal review also concluded that Mason and Rittgarn's behaviour was \"designed to elicit a confession of false reporting.\" In 2015, the commander of Lynnwood's Criminal Investigations Division said that practices had since changed. Neither Mason nor Rittgarn were disciplined. After Marie approached Mason, he offered an apology. Marie sued the city, winning $150,000. By the time of the article, Marie was married with two children.<ref name=\"Unbelievable Marshall\"/><ref name=\"Unbelievable ProPublica\"/>\n\n==Background==\n===History===\n\"An Unbelievable Story of Rape\" was written by [[Ken Armstrong (journalist)|Ken Armstrong]] and [[T. Christian Miller]]. A collaboration between [[The Marshall Project]] and [[ProPublica]], it was published on both websites on December 16, 2015.<ref name=\"Unbelievable Marshall\">{{cite web|url=https://www.themarshallproject.org/2015/12/16/an-unbelievable-story-of-rape|title=An Unbelievable Story of Rape|publisher=[[The Marshall Project]]|last1=Armstrong|first1=Ken|last2=Miller|first2=T. Christian|date=December 16, 2015|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Unbelievable ProPublica\">{{cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/false-rape-accusations-an-unbelievable-story|title=An Unbelievable Story of Rape|publisher=[[ProPublica]]|last1=Armstrong|first1=Ken|last2=Miller|first2=T. Christian|date=December 16, 2015|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref> Colorado publication ''[[Westword]]'' reprinted the article as their cover story on May 19, 2016.<ref name=\"Westword\"/> The Marshall Project and ProPublica are American non-profit online news organizations. The Marshall Project specializes in criminal justice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/17/business/media/marshall-project-kicks-off-with-look-at-legal-delays.html?_r=0|title = Marshall Project Kicks Off With Look at Legal Delays|date = November 16, 2014|accessdate = September 24, 2019|work=[[The New York Times]]|last=Somaiya|first=Ravi}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/cifamerica/2010/apr/13/pulitzer-prize-non-profit-news|title=Pulitzer progress for non-profit news|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Kennedy|first=Dan|date=April 13, 2010|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nT. Christian Miller was a senior reporter at ProPublica. Throughout 2015, he had been reporting on the failure of law enforcement to trace rapists, including the case of [[Darren Sharper]], a football player who raped nine women. Miller had discovered that an FBI database to identify serial murderers and rapists was mostly unused in the cases of rape, as most police departments fail to upload sexual assault reports.<ref name=\"about that\"/> His article \"The FBI Built a Database That Can Catch Rapists \u2014 Almost Nobody Uses It\" was published in July 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/the-fbi-built-a-database-that-can-catch-rapists-almost-nobody-uses-it|title=The FBI Built a Database That Can Catch Rapists \u2014 Almost Nobody Uses It|publisher=[[ProPublica]]|last=Miller|first=T. Christian|date=July 30, 2015|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy August 2015, Miller was working on a report about the [[Washington and Colorado serial rape cases]], with focus on the woman who recanted a report of rape after intense police interrogation, proven true years later by the rapist's conviction\u2014known in the article by her middle name \"Marie\".<ref name=\"about that\"/><ref name=\"how we reported\"/> Miller called the woman's lawyer and discovered she was in contact with Ken Armstrong of The Marshall Project, who had been working on an article about the case for several months.<ref name=\"about that\">{{cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/about-propublica-marshall-project-rape-story-collaboration|title=About That Unbelievable Story|publisher=[[ProPublica]]|last=Engelberg|first=Stephen|date=December 24, 2015|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref> The teams decided to collaborate.<ref name=\"Nieman\"/>\n\n===Research and writing===\nArmstrong's editor Joe Sexton and Miller's editor [[Bill Keller]] had worked together at ''[[The New York Times]]''. Numerous other editors contributed to the article, including managing editor Kirsten Danis of The Marshall Project.<ref name=\"Nieman\"/> As the two reporters and two primary editors were all male, the team ensured that they consulted women's input, particularly in regards to how graphic or detailed to make the description of Marie's rape.<ref name=\"Nieman\"/><ref name=\"Poynter\"/>\n\nMiller wrote the sections about the woman in Colorado, whilst Armstrong wrote the sections about the investigation in Washington. The sections are ordered alternately, with an opening paragraph about the woman in Washington being charged with false reporting.<ref name=\"Poynter\">{{cite web|url=https://www.poynter.org/reporting-editing/2016/coaches-corner-the-story-behind-an-unbelievable-story-of-rape/|title=Coaches' Corner: The story behind 'An Unbelievable Story of Rape'|publisher=[[Poynter Institute]]|last=Wilmsen|first=Steve|date=January 12, 2016|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref> The structure was proposed by Sexton. The first draft was 15,000 words in length,<ref name=\"Nieman\"/> shortened to 12,000 in the final version.<ref name=\"NYT Polk\"/> Keller and other editors recommended cutting down on the ending of the article, yielding a short epilogue.<ref name=\"Nieman\"/>\n\nAfter seven months of email and phone communication with Marie's lawyer, Marie agreed to speak to Armstrong. It was the first time she had agreed to be interviewed by a journalist.<ref name=\"Westword\"/><ref name=\"Nieman\"/> Armstrong and Miller also interviewed two of Marie's foster parents and her friend, her public defender and civil suit attorney. The pair spoke to various police officers, including Detectives Stacy Galbraith and Edna Hendershot who investigated the Colorado cases.<ref name=\"how we reported\"/> Three police officers in the Lynnwood, Washington department were interviewed, including Mason, one of the officers who handled Marie's request. The interviews were made late in the process, the department having refused earlier requests for comment.<ref name=\"Nieman\"/> The other officer, Rittgarn, declined to be interviewed. Serial rapist Marc O'Leary was also interviewed.<ref name=\"how we reported\">{{cite web|url=https://www.themarshallproject.org/2015/12/16/how-we-reported-an-unbelievable-story-of-rape|title=How We Reported 'An Unbelievable Story of Rape'|publisher=[[The Marshall Project]]|last=Armstrong|first=Ken|last2=Miller|first2=T. Christian|date=December 16, 2015|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref> A brief audio recording of Marie describing her rape is included in the article.<ref name=\"Unbelievable ProPublica\"/>\n\nFor the article, Armstrong and Miller made [[public records request]]s to police departments and prosecuting attorney's offices in Washington and Colorado. They received thousands of pages of documents, including investigative reports, case reviews, crime scene photographs and footage of surveillance and O'Leary after his arrest. News coverage, criminal justice guidelines and court transcripts were also consulted.<ref name=\"how we reported\"/> Extracts of an external report made of the police department that investigated Marie's case were made public for the first time in the article.<ref name=\"Unbelievable Marshall\"/>\n\n==Response==\nThe article won the 2015 [[George Polk Award]] for Justice Reporting, presented by [[Long Island University]], and the 2016 Al Nakkula Award for Police Reporting, awarded by the [[University of Colorado Boulder]] and [[Denver Press Club]].<ref name=\"UofC\"/><ref name=\"NYT Polk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/15/nyregion/new-york-times-investigation-of-navy-seals-among-winners-of-2015-polk-awards.html|title=New York Times Journalists Among Winners of 2015 Polk Awards|work=[[The New York Times]]|last=Barron|first=James|date=February 14, 2016|accessdate=September 24, 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref> It also won the 2016 [[Pulitzer Prize for Explanatory Reporting]], the article being described as \"a startling examination and expos\u00e9 of law enforcement's enduring failures to investigate reports of rape properly and to comprehend the traumatic effects on its victims\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulitzer.org/prize-winners-by-category/207|title=Explanatory Reporting|publisher=Pulitzer Prize Board|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulitzer.org/winners/t-christian-miller-propublica-and-ken-armstrong-marshall-project|title=T. Christian Miller of ProPublica and Ken Armstrong of The Marshall Project|publisher=Pulitzer Prize Board|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> It was a finalist in the 2016 [[National Magazine Awards]] in the Feature Writing category.<ref name=\"Nieman\">{{cite web|url=https://nieman.harvard.edu/stories/notable-narrative-ken-armstrong-t-christian-miller-and-an-unbelievable-story-of-rape/|title=Notable Narrative: Ken Armstrong, T. Christian Miller and \"An Unbelievable Story of Rape\"|publisher=[[Nieman Foundation for Journalism]]|last=Fitzgerald|first=Michael|date=January 26, 2016|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nRusty Foster of ''[[Fast Company]]'' described the article as \"impeccably reported and written, and completely devastating\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3054755/today-in-tabs-look-at-these-rich-idiots-suffering-on-mars|title=Today in Tabs: Look At These Rich Idiots Suffering On Mars|work=[[Fast Company]]|last=Foster|first=Rusty|date=December 16, 2015}}</ref> Nora Caplan-Bricker of ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' reflected that \"Marie's story helps remind us that false reports of rape are the exception, not the rule\", believing that the article shows the \"ruinous consequences\" and \"ubiquity\" of rape victims being disbelieved.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/human-interest/2015/12/rape-victim-who-recanted-story-is-vindicated.html|title=A Haunting Story That Shows the Consequences\u2014and the Ubiquity\u2014of Doubting Rape Victims|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|last=Caplan-Bricker|first=Nora|date=December 16, 2015|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> Writing for the alternative Wisconsin newspaper ''[[Isthmus (newspaper)|Isthmus]]'', Bill Lueders praised the article and compared it to his own reporting about a similar case from 1997 to 2001, where a woman was charged by police after ostensibly making a false report of rape, but was later proven truthful by DNA evidence leading to her rapist's conviction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://isthmus.com/news/news/national-rape-story-has-madison-parallels/|title=National rape story has Madison parallels|work=[[Isthmus (newspaper)|Isthmus]]|last=Lueders|first=Bill|date=December 21, 2015|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe University of Colorado Boulder reported in 2016 that law enforcement officials had requested to use the article in training. Jennifer Gentile Long, CEO of AEquitas: The Prosecutors' Resource on Violence Against Women, commented that the article presented an \"extraordinary learning opportunity for both criminal justice professionals and ordinary citizens alike\".<ref name=\"UofC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.colorado.edu/today/2016/04/15/team-wins-al-nakkula-award-police-reporting|title=Team wins Al Nakkula Award for Police Reporting|publisher=[[University of Colorado Boulder]]|last=Lock|first=Elizabeth|date=April 15, 2016|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref> Journalist [[Pamela Colloff]] referenced the article as an example of good reporting on criminal justice, as it is told from the perspective of a survivor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nieman.harvard.edu/stories/covering-failures-in-the-justice-system-with-patience-for-facts-and-sensitivity-to-victims/|title=Covering failures in the justice system with patience for facts and sensitivity to victims|publisher=[[Nieman Foundation for Journalism]]|last=Tarrant|first=David|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Subsequent media==\n\"An Unbelievable Story of Rape\" was published on December 16, 2015. In the days following, Miller and Armstrong published two subsequent articles: \"A Brutal Crime, Often Terribly Investigated\" enumerated five recommendations for police institutions to improve their handling of rape cases, while \"Rape is Rape, Isn't It?\" commented on the changing definition of rape used by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themarshallproject.org/2015/12/18/a-brutal-crime-often-terribly-investigated|title=A Brutal Crime, Often Terribly Investigated|publisher=[[The Marshall Project]]|last=Armstrong|first=Ken|last2=Miller|first2=T. Christian|date=December 18, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/flawed-rape-statistics-hamper-understanding-and-preventing-the-crime|title=Rape is Rape, Isn't It?|publisher=[[ProPublica]]|last=Armstrong|first=Ken|last2=Miller|first2=T. Christian|date=December 18, 2015|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{external media\n|audio1 = [https://longform.org/posts/longform-podcast-201-t-christian-miller-and-ken-armstrong ''#201: T. Christian Miller and Ken Armstrong'']<br>Episode of ''Longform''.\n|audio2 = [https://www.thisamericanlife.org/581/anatomy-of-doubt ''An Anatomy of Doubt'']<br>Episode of ''[[This American Life]]''.\n|audio3 = [https://www.upr.org/post/revisiting-pulitzer-prize-winning-journalist-ken-armstrong-tuesdays-access-utah ''Revisiting Pulitzer Prize-Winning Journalist Ken Armstrong On Tuesday's Access Utah'']<br>Episode of ''Access Utah''.\n}}\n\nIn December 2015, ProPublica published a podcast episode where Miller and Armstrong discussed the article.<ref>{{cite podcast |host=Cynthia Gordy Giwa |title=How Almost Getting Scooped Brought Two Competing Reporters Together |publisher=[[ProPublica]] |date=December 24, 2015 |url=https://www.propublica.org/podcast/how-almost-getting-scooped-brought-two-competing-reporters-together/ |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> At the [[Investigative Reporters and Editors]]' 2016 conference, the pair gave a talk about their experience writing the article.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ire.org/events-and-training/event/2199/2570/|title=Constructing the narrative: An unbelievable story of rape|publisher=[[Investigative Reporters and Editors]]|last1=Armstrong|first=Ken|last2=Miller|first2=T. Christian|date=June 17, 2016|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> In July 2016, they appeared on the ''Longform'' podcast to discuss the article.<ref name=\"Westword\">{{cite web|url=https://www.westword.com/news/the-backstory-of-how-the-pulitzer-winning-unbelievable-story-of-rape-came-to-be-8134322|title=The Backstory of How the Pulitzer-Winning \"Unbelievable Story of Rape\" Came to Be|work=[[Westword]]|last=Walker|first=Chris|date=July 26, 2016|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref> Armstrong appeared on [[Utah Public Radio]] in November 2016, discussing the article on ''Access Utah''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.upr.org/post/revisiting-pulitzer-prize-winning-journalist-ken-armstrong-tuesdays-access-utah|title=Revisiting Pulitzer Prize-Winning Journalist Ken Armstrong On Tuesday's Access Utah|publisher=[[Utah Public Radio]]|last=Williams|first=Tom|date=November 22, 2016|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==={{anchor|Anatomy of Doubt}} ''An Anatomy of Doubt''===\n'''''An Anatomy of Doubt''''' is the 581st episode of the American radio program and podcast ''[[This American Life]]''. It adapts \"An Unbelievable Story of Rape\". Credited as a collaboration with The Marshall Project and ProPublica, it debuted on February 26, 2016. The hour-long episode features [[Ira Glass]], Ken Armstrong and [[Robyn Semien]] and includes interviews with Marie, Mason and two of Marie's foster parents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisamericanlife.org/581/anatomy-of-doubt|title=Anatomy of Doubt|work=[[This American Life]]|date=February 26, 2016|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themarshallproject.org/2016/02/25/this-american-life-unbelievable-story-rape|title=Listen to Our First Collaboration with \"This American Life\"|publisher=[[The Marshall Project]]|date=February 25, 2016|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Westword\"/>\n\n==={{anchor|A False Report: A True Story of Rape in America}} ''A False Report''===\n<!-- Could be expanded into an article, for which see also: reviews on Crown Publishing page; https://www.npr.org/2018/02/06/583778370/a-false-report-highlights-how-women-who-report-sexual-assault-are-treated -->\nArmstrong and Miller adapted their article and additional research into a 304-page book, '''''A False Report: A True Story of Rape in America'''''. It was published on February 6, 2018 by the [[Crown Publishing Group]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crownpublishing.com/archives/news/false-report-true-story-rape-america|title=A False Report: A True Story of Rape in America By T. Christian Miller and Ken Armstrong|publisher=[[Crown Publishing Group]]|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themarysue.com/false-report-believe-women/|title=''A False Report'' Reminds Us of What Happens When You Don't Believe Women|work=[[The Mary Sue]]|author=Princess Weekes|date=January 19, 2018|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref> The book expands upon details of the case like O'Leary's perspective and subjects such as [[victim blaming]] and [[social media]] harassment.<ref name=\"IT False Report\"/><ref name=\"ST False Report\"/> Mason was interviewed for the book, but Rittgarn refused to speak to the authors without being paid.<ref name=\"ST False Report\">{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/books/a-false-report-looks-at-a-local-story-of-rape-and-its-aftermath/|title='A False Report' looks at a local story of rape and its aftermath|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|last=Rowe|first=Claudia|date=February 3, 2018|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe book received mostly positive critical reviews,<!-- Star Tribune, NYT, Seattle Times mostly positive; Irish Times mostly negative --> with Hamilton Cain of ''[[Star Tribune]]'' calling it an \"instant true-crime classic\".<ref name=\"Star\">{{cite web|url=https://www.startribune.com/review-a-false-report-a-true-story-of-rape-in-america-by-t-christian-miller-and-ken-armstrong/474226823/|title=Review: 'A False Report: A True Story of Rape in America,' by T. Christian Miller and Ken Armstrong|work=[[Star Tribune]]|last=Cain|first=Hamilton|date=February 16, 2018|accessdate=April 12, 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Emily Bazelon of ''[[The New York Times]]'' praised that the authors \"tell their story plainly, expertly and well\",<ref name=\"NYT False Report\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/06/books/review/a-false-report-t-christian-miller-ken-armstrong.html|title=The Lesson Here Is Listen to the Victim|work=[[The New York Times]]|last=Bazelon|first=Emily|date=March 6, 2018|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> and the style of alternating between Marie's story and the other Denver sexual assaults was praised by Claudie Rowe of ''[[The Seattle Times]]'' and Cain.<ref name=\"ST False Report\"/><ref name=\"Star\"/> However, though Rosita Boland of ''[[The Irish Times]]'' enjoyed the early sections of the book, she found it to have a \"curiously flat style overall, without any distinctive voice\".<ref name=\"IT False Report\">{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/a-false-report-review-a-powerful-story-about-a-serial-rapist-that-falls-flat-1.3388458|title=A False Report review: a powerful story about a serial rapist that falls flat|work=[[The Irish Times]]|last=Boland|first=Rosita|date=February 17, 2018|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===''Unbelievable''===\n{{main|Unbelievable (miniseries)}}\nThe [[Netflix]] miniseries ''Unbelievable'' is an eight-part adaptation of \"An Unbelievable Story of Rape\", also drawing from ''An Anatomy of Doubt'' and ''A False Report''. It premiered on September 13, 2019. The main characters are based on Marie Adler ([[Kaitlyn Dever]]) and Detectives Edna Hendershot and Stacy Galbraith, who were renamed as Grace Rasmussen ([[Toni Collette]]) and Karen Duvall ([[Merritt Wever]]). Marie, Armstrong and Miller were consulted during the production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/09/17/unbelievable-true-story-behind-netflixs-gripping-new-drama-about-women-who-solved-serial-rape-case/|title=The true story behind 'Unbelievable,' Netflix's gripping new drama about the women who solved a serial rape case|work=[[The Washington Post]]|last=Butler|first=Bethonie|date=September 17, 2019|accessdate=September 25, 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/07/unbelievable-trailer-sexual-assault-toni-colette-netflix-1202158956/ |title='Unbelievable' Trailer: Sexual Assault Victim Fights to Be Heard in Toni Colette-Starring Netflix Drama |last=Zilko |first=Christian |date=July 18, 2019 |website=IndieWire |access-date=July 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/how-a-pulitzer-prize-winning-investigation-became-netflixs-unbelievable-1239342|title=How a Pulitzer Prize-Winning Investigation Became Netflix's 'Unbelievable'|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last=Kilkenny|first=Katie|date=September 13, 2019|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNetflix reported that \"Unbelievable\" had been garnered 32 million views by the end of September, where a \"view\" entailed watching at least 70% of an episode. This made it the seventh-most viewed television series on the platform from August 2018 to September 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/tv-radio-web/netflix-has-revealed-its-most-watched-content-you-might-be-surprised-1.4060255|title=Netflix has revealed its most-watched content. You might be surprised|work=[[The Irish Times]]|last=Lee|first=Benjamin|date=October 23, 2019|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The program was nominated for numerous awards, including four nominations each at the [[Golden Globe Awards]] and the [[Critics' Choice Television Awards]], with one win at the latter.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2020-golden-globes-nominations-full-list-1259626 |title=Golden Globes: Full List of Nominations |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=December 9, 2019 |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://tvline.com/2019/12/08/critics-choice-awards-nominations-2020-full-list-tv-nominees/ |title=Critics' Choice Awards 2020: Fleabag, Watchmen, When They See Us, Unbelievable Among TV Nominees |website=[[TVLine]] |date=December 8, 2019 |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/critics-choice-awards-2020-winners-list-1202828353/|title=Critics' Choice Awards: 'Once Upon A Time In Hollywood' Wins Best Picture, Netflix And HBO Among Top Honorees \u2013 Full Winners List|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=Ramos|first=Dino-Ray|last2=Boucher|first2=Geoff|date=January 12, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the series has a rating of 98%, based on 82 reviews, with the summary: \"Heartbreaking and powerful, ''Unbelievable'' transcends familiar true-crime beats by shifting its gaze to survivors of abuse, telling their stories with grace and gravity.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/unbelievable/s01|title=Unbelievable: Season 1 (2019)|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the program has a rating of 83 out of 100 based on 25 reviews, indicating universal acclaim.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/unbelievable|title=Unbelievable|publisher=[[CBS]]|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2015 works]]\n[[Category:George Polk Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Investigative journalism]]\n[[Category:Pulitzer Prize for Investigative Reporting winners]]\n[[Category:Works about rape]]\n[[Category:Works about police officers]]\n[[Category:Works about American law enforcement agencies]]\n", "name_user": "SounderBruce", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eResearch and writing:state already mentioned above; using proper name for entity", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/An_Unbelievable_Story_of_Rape"}
{"title_page": "Valdemar Bandolowski", "text_new": "{{short description|Danish sailor and Olympic champion|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{MedalTableTop||160px|Valdemar Bandolowski}}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[Sailing (sport)|sailing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{DEN}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[1976 Summer Olympics|1976 Montreal]] | [[Sailing at the 1976 Summer Olympics|Soling class]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[1980 Summer Olympics|1980 Moscow]] | [[Sailing at the 1980 Summer Olympics|Soling class]]}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n\n'''Valdemar Bandolowski''' (born 17 February 1946 in [[Esb\u00f8nderup]]) is a [[Denmark|Danish]] [[sailor]] and Olympic champion.\n\nHe won a gold medal in the ''[[Soling|Soling Class]]'' at the [[1976 Summer Olympics]] in [[Montreal]],<ref name=db-ol-YAT1976>[http://www.databaseolympics.com/games/gamessport.htm?g=19&sp=YAT \"1976 Summer Olympics &ndash; Montreal, Canada &ndash; Sailing\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917043711/http://www.databaseolympics.com/games/gamessport.htm?g=19&sp=YAT |date=2008-09-17 }} ''databaseOlympics.com'' (Retrieved on June 4, 2008)</ref> and again at the [[1980 Summer Olympics]] in [[Moscow]].<ref name=db-ol-YAT1980>[http://www.databaseolympics.com/games/gamessport.htm?g=20&sp=YAT \"1980 Summer Olympics &ndash; Moscow, Soviet Union &ndash; Sailing\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070827094711/http://www.databaseolympics.com/games/gamessport.htm?g=20&sp=YAT |date=2007-08-27 }} ''databaseOlympics.com'' (Retrieved on June 4, 2008)</ref>\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Soling}}\n{{Footer World Champions Soling}}\n{{Footer European Champions Soling}}\n{{Footer Dutch Championship Winners in Soling}}\n{{Footer West German Championship Winners in Soling}}\n{{Footer Swedish Championship Winners in Soling}}\n{{Footer World Champions Dragon}}\n{{Footer Dragon Gold Cup}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bandolowski, Valdemar}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Danish male sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:Olympic sailors of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Denmark]]\n[[Category:Danish people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in sailing]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1972 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1976 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1980 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling]]\n[[Category:People from Gribskov Municipality]]\n[[Category:European Champions Soling]]\n[[Category:Soling class world champions]]\n{{Denmark-Olympic-medalist-stub}}\n{{Denmark-yachtracing-bio-stub}}\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1980 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Danish sailor and Olympic champion|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{MedalTableTop||160px|Valdemar Bandolowski}}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[Sailing (sport)|sailing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{DEN}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[1976 Summer Olympics|1976 Montreal]] | [[Sailing at the 1976 Summer Olympics|Soling class]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[1980 Summer Olympics|1980 Moscow]] | [[Sailing at the 1980 Summer Olympics|Soling class]]}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n\n'''Valdemar Bandolowski''' (born 17 February 1946 in [[Esb\u00f8nderup]]) is a [[Denmark|Danish]] [[sailor]] and Olympic champion.\n\nHe won a gold medal in the ''[[Soling|Soling Class]]'' at the [[1976 Summer Olympics]] in [[Montreal]],<ref name=db-ol-YAT1976>[http://www.databaseolympics.com/games/gamessport.htm?g=19&sp=YAT \"1976 Summer Olympics &ndash; Montreal, Canada &ndash; Sailing\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917043711/http://www.databaseolympics.com/games/gamessport.htm?g=19&sp=YAT |date=2008-09-17 }} ''databaseOlympics.com'' (Retrieved on June 4, 2008)</ref> and again at the [[1980 Summer Olympics]] in [[Moscow]].<ref name=db-ol-YAT1980>[http://www.databaseolympics.com/games/gamessport.htm?g=20&sp=YAT \"1980 Summer Olympics &ndash; Moscow, Soviet Union &ndash; Sailing\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070827094711/http://www.databaseolympics.com/games/gamessport.htm?g=20&sp=YAT |date=2007-08-27 }} ''databaseOlympics.com'' (Retrieved on June 4, 2008)</ref>\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Soling}}\n{{Footer World Champions Dragon}}\n{{Footer World Champions Soling}}\n{{Footer Dragon Gold Cup}}\n{{Footer Dutch Championship Winners in Soling}}\n{{Footer West German Championship Winners in Soling}}\n{{Footer Swedish Championship Winners in Soling}}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bandolowski, Valdemar}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Danish male sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:Olympic sailors of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Denmark]]\n[[Category:Danish people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in sailing]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1972 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1976 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1980 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling]]\n[[Category:People from Gribskov Municipality]]\n[[Category:European Champions Soling]]\n[[Category:Soling class world champions]]\n{{Denmark-Olympic-medalist-stub}}\n{{Denmark-yachtracing-bio-stub}}\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1980 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n", "name_user": "Dragon Genoa", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valdemar_Bandolowski"}
{"title_page": "Gervais Carpentier", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = Brigadier General\n| name          = F.G. Carpentier\n| honorific_suffix = CD\n| image         = \n| allegiance    = [[Canada]]\n| branch        = [[Canadian Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1987- Present\n| rank          = [[File:Canadian Army OF-6.svg|20px]][[Brigadier General]]\n| unit          = [[Royal 22nd Regiment]], [[Joint Task Force 2]]\n| commands      = 2nd Battalion [[Royal 22e R\u00e9giment]], [[Royal Military College Saint-Jean]], [[2nd Canadian Division]]\n| battles       = [[Bosnian War]],\n[[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n| alma_mater    = [[Royal Military College Saint-Jean]], [[Royal Military College of Canada]], [[Canadian Forces College]]\n}}\n\n[[Brigadier general|'''Brigadier General''']] '''F.G. Carpentier, [[Canadian Forces' Decoration|CD]]''' is currently serving as the [[Commanding officer|Commanding Officer]] of the [[2nd Canadian Division]], a position he has held since August 15, 2019 .<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.45enord.ca/2019/08/2e-division-du-canada-carignan-out-carpentier-in-photos-video/|title=2e Division du Canada: Carignan out, Carpentier in [PHOTOS/VID\u00c9O] \u2013 45eNord.ca|last=Godbout|first=Jacques N.|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n'''Gervais Carpentier''' would graduate in 1992 with a bachelor's degree in business administration from the [[Royal Military College Saint-Jean]]. He would later obtain a master's degree from the [[Royal Military College of Canada]]. In 2009 he would graduate from  the [[Canadian Forces College]] Joint Command and Staff Program and in 2017 from the National Security Program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.r22er.com/Titulaires/Biographies/Carpentier_G_Bgen.html|title=Royal 22e R\u00e9giment|website=www.r22er.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Military career ==\n'''Carpentier''' enrolled into the [[Canadian Armed Forces]] in 1987 as an [[Officer Cadet (Canada)|Officer Cadet]] at the [[Royal Military College Saint-Jean]]. After graduating he would assume his trade as an Infantry Officer in the 5th Canadian Mechanized Brigade. In 1993 '''Carpentier''' would deploy to [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] as a Platoon Commander, and again in 1995 to [[Croatia]] during the [[Bosnian War]]. In 1997 Carpentier would again deploy as a platoon commander to [[Haiti]] with 3rd Battalion [[Royal 22nd Regiment|R22R]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Reunion Weekend 2018|publisher=Royal Military College Saint-Jean|year=2018|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> After Haiti he would be an instructor at the [[Combat Training Centre|Infantry School in Gagetown]] from 1997\u20131999. '''Carpentier''' would go on to serve in the [[Canadian Special Operations Forces Command]] as a Troop Commander and eventually command an assault squadron within [[Joint Task Force 2]].  During his time with [[Joint Task Force 2]] Carpentier would deploy to Afghanistan in 2002 and 2007. From 2009 to 2011 he would serve in the [[CANSOFCOM]] HQ. In 2011 he would serve as the military assistant to the Deputy Commander at NATO's [[Allied Joint Force Command Naples|Joint Forces Command Naples in Italy]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nCarpentier would serve as the Chief of Staff for the 5th Canadian Mechanized Brigade Group in 2013. In 2014 Carpantier would become the [[Commanding officer|Commanding Officer]] of [[Royal 22nd Regiment|2nd Battalion Royal 22 Regiment]] and would hold this position until 2016. In 2017 Carpentier would become the [[Commandant]] of the [[Royal Military College Saint-Jean]] where he would oversee the re-introduction of a university courses to obtain a degree at the Collage. In 2019 Gervais Carpentier would be promoted to the rank of [[Brigadier general|Brigadier General]] after becoming the Commanding Officer of the [[2nd Canadian Division]] on August 15, 2019 taking over from [[Major general|Major General]] [[Jennie Carignan]] after she took command of the NATO mission in Iraq.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://montreal.ctvnews.ca/brigadier-general-promoted-to-major-general-1.4547795|title=Brigadier-General promoted to Major-General|last=Staff|first=CTV Montreal|date=2019-08-13|website=Montreal|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = Brigadier General\n| name          = F.G. Carpentier\n| honorific_suffix = CD\n| image         = \n| allegiance    = [[Canada]]\n| branch        = [[Canadian Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1987- Present\n| rank          = [[File:Canadian Army OF-6.svg|20px]][[Brigadier General]]\n| unit          = [[Royal 22nd Regiment]], [[Joint Task Force 2]]\n| commands      = 2nd Battalion [[Royal 22e R\u00e9giment]], [[Royal Military College Saint-Jean]], [[2nd Canadian Division]]\n| battles       = [[Bosnian War]],\n[[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n| alma_mater    = [[Royal Military College Saint-Jean]], [[Royal Military College of Canada]], [[Canadian Forces College]]\n}}\n\n[[Brigadier general|'''Brigadier General''']] '''F.G. Carpentier, [[Canadian Forces' Decoration|CD]]''' is currently serving as the [[Commanding officer|Commanding Officer]] of the [[2nd Canadian Division]], a position he has held since August 15th 2019 .<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.45enord.ca/2019/08/2e-division-du-canada-carignan-out-carpentier-in-photos-video/|title=2e Division du Canada: Carignan out, Carpentier in [PHOTOS/VID\u00c9O] \u2013 45eNord.ca|last=Godbout|first=Jacques N.|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n'''Gervais Carpentier''' would graduate in 1992 with a bachelor's degree in business administration from the [[Royal Military College Saint-Jean]]. He would later obtain a Master's degree from the [[Royal Military College of Canada]]. In 2009 he would graduate from  the [[Canadian Forces College]] Joint Command and Staff Program and in 2017 from the National Security Program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.r22er.com/Titulaires/Biographies/Carpentier_G_Bgen.html|title=Royal 22e R\u00e9giment|website=www.r22er.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Military career ==\n'''Carpentier''' enrolled into the [[Canadian Armed Forces]] in 1987 as a [[Officer Cadet (Canada)|Officer Cadet]] at the [[Royal Military College Saint-Jean]]. After graduating he would assume his trade as an Infantry Officer in the 5th Canadian Mechanized Brigade. In 1993 '''Carpentier''' would deploy to [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] as a Platoon Commander, and again in 1995 to [[Croatia]] during the [[Bosnian War]]. In 1997 Carpentier would again deploy as a platoon commander to [[Haiti]] with 3rd Battalion [[Royal 22nd Regiment|R22R]]. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Reunion Weekend 2018|publisher=Royal Military College Saint-Jean|year=2018|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> After Haiti he would be an instructor at the [[Combat Training Centre|Infantry School in Gagetown]] from 1997-1999. '''Carpentier''' would go on to serve in the [[Canadian Special Operations Forces Command]] as a Troop Commander and eventually command an assault squadron within [[Joint Task Force 2]].  During his time with [[Joint Task Force 2]] Carpentier would deploy to Afghanistan in 2002 and 2007. From 2009 to 2011 he would serve in the [[CANSOFCOM]] HQ. In 2011 he would serve as the military assistant to the Deputy Commander at NATO's [[Allied Joint Force Command Naples|Joint Forces Command Naples in Italy]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nCarpentier would serve as the Chief of Staff for the 5th Canadian Mechanized Brigade Group in 2013. In 2014 Carpantier would become the [[Commanding officer|Commanding Officer]] of [[Royal 22nd Regiment|2nd Battalion Royal 22 Regiment]] and would hold this position until 2016. In 2017 Carpentier would become the [[Commandant]] of the [[Royal Military College Saint-Jean]] where he would oversee the re-introduction of a university courses to obtain a degree at the Collage. In 2019 Gervais Carpentier would be promoted to the rank of [[Brigadier general|Brigadier General]] after becoming the Commanding Officer of the [[2nd Canadian Division]] on August 15th 2019 taking over from [[Major general|Major General]] [[Jennie Carignan]] after she took command of the NATO mission in Iraq.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://montreal.ctvnews.ca/brigadier-general-promoted-to-major-general-1.4547795|title=Brigadier-General promoted to Major-General|last=Staff|first=CTV Montreal|date=2019-08-13|website=Montreal|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==Reference==\n", "name_user": "Kaltenmeyer", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, replaced: a [[Officer \u2192  an [[Officer, added [[CAT:UNCAT|uncategorised]] tag,typo(s) fixed: Master's degree \u2192 master's degree, 1997-1999 \u2192 1997\u20131999", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gervais_Carpentier"}
{"title_page": "Denver Pioneers men's lacrosse", "text_new": "{{Infobox college lacrosse team\n| name      = Denver Pioneers\n|image = Denver Pioneers logo.svg\n|image_size = \n| caption       = \n| university    = [[University of Denver]]\n| nickname = [[Denver Pioneers|Pioneers]]\n| founded       = 1966, [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] since 1999\n| location      = [[Denver]], [[Colorado]]\n| stadium       = Peter Barton Lacrosse Stadium\n| capacity      = 2,000\n| conference    = [[Big East Conference]]\n| coach         = [[Bill Tierney]]\n| tenure        = since&nbsp;2009\n| pre_NCAA      =\n| NCAA_champion = (1) \u2013 2015\n| NCAA_runner   =\n| NCAA_semi     = (5) \u2013 2011, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2017\n| NCAA_quarter  = (7) \u2013 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2017, 2018\n| NCAA_tourney  = (11) \u2013 2006, 2008, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018\n| conf_tourney  = (3) \u2013 2011, 2014, 2015\n| conf_champion = (13) \u2013 2003, 2005, 2006, 2008, 2010, 2011, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019\n}}\n\nThe '''Denver Pioneers men's lacrosse team''' represents the [[University of Denver]] (DU) in [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[college lacrosse]].  The DU men's lacrosse program was first introduced in 1966 as a club sport.  The program alternated between varsity and club status until entering Division I in 1999.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.denverpioneers.com/sports/m-lacros/archive/history.html |title=Men's Lacrosse History | work=DenverPioneers.com | accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSince the 2014 season, the Pioneers have competed as an associate member of the [[Big East Conference]]. DU was initially a Big East member in men's lacrosse only,<ref>{{cite news | last=Foy | first=Terry | title=Denver Joins Big East Men's Lacrosse Starting in 2014 | url=http://insidelacrosse.com/news/2013/05/29/sources-denver-likely-join-big-east-mens-lacrosse | accessdate=February 13, 2015 | work=Inside Lacrosse | date=August 6, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609112800/http://insidelacrosse.com/news/2013/05/29/sources-denver-likely-join-big-east-mens-lacrosse | archive-date=June 9, 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref> but added women's lacrosse to its Big East membership in advance of the 2017 season.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.bigeast.com/news/2016/5/3/WLAX_0503164846.aspx |title=Denver Added To BIG EAST Women\u2019s Lacrosse Lineup |publisher=Big East Conference |date=May 3, 2016 |accessdate=May 4, 2016}}</ref> Before DU's move to the Big East for the 2014 season, it had been a member of the [[Great Western Lacrosse League]] from 1998 to 2009 and then the [[ECAC Lacrosse League]] from 2010 to 2013.\n\nThrough 2015, Denver has an all-time varsity record of 272&ndash;203&ndash;1. In Division I alone, they are 173&ndash;95.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/denv/sports/m-lacros/auto_pdf/2014-15/prospectus/prospectus.pdf | title=2015 Men's Lacrosse Media Guide | work=University of Denver | accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"2015 title\">{{cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/story/_/id/12950697/denver-pioneers-beat-maryland-terrapins-first-ncaa-men-lacrosse-title |title=Pioneers win 1st men's lacrosse title |publisher=[[ESPN.com]]|date=May 25, 2015 |accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref> Denver plays its home games at Peter Barton Lacrosse Stadium, which has a capacity of 2,000 people.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.denverpioneers.com/facilities/peter-barton-lacrosse-stadium.html | title=Peter Barton Lacrosse Stadium | work=DenverPioneers.com | accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\n[[File:D1 Lacrosse.jpg|thumb|left|Denver plays Maryland in 2006]]\n\nThe [[University of Denver]] first began sponsoring men's lacrosse as a club sport in 1966 under coach Pete Richardson. Over the next 24 years, the team would alternate between varsity and club status in the [[Rocky Mountain Lacrosse Conference|RMLA]], a member of the [[US Lacrosse Intercollegiate Associates]] (USLIA). In 1991, Denver transitioned into [[NCAA Division II]] as a member of the RMILL before making the full transition to [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] with the rest of DU sports in 1999. The Pioneers first joined the [[Great Western Lacrosse League]] (GWLL) as a charter member in 1994, although the Pioneers would not compete in the conference as a full Division I member until 1999.\n\nIn 1999, Denver hired Jamie Munro as head coach for the team's inaugural season in Division I and the GWLL. Under Munro, the Pioneers would win their first conference regular season title after finishing with a 4&ndash;1 conference record (tied with [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish men's lacrosse|Notre Dame]] and [[Ohio State Buckeyes men's lacrosse|Ohio State]]). After winning the GWLL outright in 2006 with a 5&ndash;0 conference record, Denver earned a bid to their first [[2006 NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship|NCAA Tournament]], where they would fall 16&ndash;8 to [[Maryland Terrapins men's lacrosse|Maryland]]. Two years later the Pioneers again shared the GWLL regular season title with Notre Dame and Ohio State, but earned an at-large bid to the [[2008 NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship|2008 NCAA Tournament]] with a 10&ndash;7 overall record. Denver would lose to Maryland once again, this time 10&ndash;7.\n\nAfter finishing 1&ndash;4 in the conference and 7&ndash;8 overall in 2009, Jamie Munro resigned. Munro finished with a 90&ndash;70 record as head coach of the Pioneers, securing four GWLL Championship titles (2003, 2005, 2006, 2008) and two NCAA postseason tournament appearances (2006, 2008). He was also named GWLL Coach of the Year in 2000 and 2006.\n\n==Bill Tierney era==\nIn 2009, [[Lacrosse Museum and National Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] coach [[Bill Tierney]] was named head coach of the Pioneers. Tierney was previously the coach at [[Princeton Tigers men's lacrosse|Princeton]] for 22 years, earning 6 NCAA championships in 9 years, appearing in 8 championship games, 9 Final Fours and 11 Ivy League championships.\n\nIn 2010, the Pioneers tied the program-best record of 12&ndash;5 and earned the [[ECAC Lacrosse League|ECAC]] regular season title after completing a 7&ndash;0 conference record. Denver would earn just their third [[2010 NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship|NCAA Tournament]] birth, where they would lose to [[Stony Brook Seawolves men's lacrosse|Stony Brook]], 9-7, in the first round.\n\nIn 2011, the Pioneers completed a 15&ndash;3 record, again going undefeated in the ECAC at 6&ndash;0 to capture the conference regular season and tournament championships. In the [[2011 NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship|2011 NCAA Tournament]]  the No. 6-seeded Pioneers hosted No. 11 [[Villanova Wildcats men's lacrosse|Villanova]] in front of a standing room-only home crowd of 2,575. In the first NCAA Tournament game to ever be held west of the Mississippi River, Denver earned its first ever tournament win, beating Villanova 13-10 to advance to the quarterfinals. In the quarterfinal round Denver defeated [[Johns Hopkins Blue Jays men's lacrosse|Johns Hopkins]] 14-9 at [[James M. Shuart Stadium]] in [[Hempstead (town), New York|Hempstead, New York]] to earn a spot in the NCAA Final Four. At [[M&T Bank Stadium]] in [[Baltimore]] the Pioneers would fall to the eventual champion [[Virginia Cavaliers men's lacrosse|Virginia]] by a score of 14-8.\n\nFollowing the school's first NCAA Final Four, the Pioneers completed a 9&ndash;7 record while going 3&ndash;3in the ECAC. Although the 9&ndash;7 regular season tally did not compare to previous season records, Denver lost six one&ndash;goal games, including four in overtime throughout the season. The Pioneers would still make the [[2012 NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship|2012 NCAA Tournament]] thanks to one of the toughest schedules in the country. In the first round the Pioneers defeated [[North Carolina Tar Heels men's lacrosse|North Carolina]] 16-14 in [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina]], but would go on to lose to conference rival and eventual national champion [[Loyola Greyhounds men's lacrosse|Loyola-Maryland]] for the third time, by a score of 10&ndash;9 in front of 13,390 fans at the [[Navy\u2013Marine Corps Memorial Stadium]] in [[Annapolis, Maryland]].\n\nIn 2013, Denver would once again capture the ECAC regular season crown after earning a 6&ndash;1 conference record and an 11&ndash;3 overall record. After the 11th week of the season Denver would earn the No. 1 ranking in both the Nike/Inside Lacrosse Media Poll and the USILA Coaches Poll, the first time in program history that they have been ranked No. 1 in the country. Denver would go on to lose to [[Ohio State Buckeyes men's lacrosse|Ohio State]] in the ECAC title game, but the Pioneers would earn an at-large bid to the [[2013 NCAA Division I Men's Lacrosse Championship|2013 NCAA Tournament]]. In the first round Denver would host just the second NCAA Tournament game held west of the Mississippi at a sold out Peter Barton Lacrosse Stadium. A record 2,621 fans were on hand to see Denver top [[Albany Great Danes men's lacrosse|Albany]] 19&ndash;14. In the quarterfinals, Denver faced a rematch of a 2011 first round game against [[North Carolina Tar Heels men's lacrosse|North Carolina]], this time at [[Lucas Oil Stadium]] in [[Indianapolis|Indianapolis, Indiana]]. After falling behind 6&ndash;0 early on, the Pioneers were behind 9&ndash;4 at the half but would go 8&ndash;2 in the second half, including 5&ndash;1 in the final quarter to win 12&ndash;11. Denver became the first team in Men\u2019s Lacrosse Championship Quarterfinal history to win after trailing by five goals or more. In the Pioneer's second semifinal appearance in three years, Denver would fall to [[Syracuse Orange men's lacrosse|Syracuse]] 9&ndash;8 at [[Lincoln Financial Field]] in [[Philadelphia|Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]. Denver would end the season 14&ndash;5 and ranked No. 4 in the final polls.\n\nThe 2015 season was the most successful in DU lacrosse history. The Pioneers won both the Big East regular-season<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.denverpioneers.com/sports/m-lacros/recaps/042515aaa.html |title=[5/6] Denver Wins Big East Crown With 18-11 Win Over [16/17] Marquette |publisher=Denver Pioneers |date=April 25, 2015 |accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref> and tournament titles,<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.denverpioneers.com/sports/m-lacros/recaps/050215aaa.html |title=[4/3] Denver Repeats as Big East Champs With 16-8 Win Over [13/12] Georgetown |publisher=Denver Pioneers |date=May 2, 2015 |accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref> earning a #4 seed in that year's NCAA tournament.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.denverpioneers.com/sports/m-lacros/spec-rel/050315aac.html |title=Fourth-Seeded Denver to Host Brown in NCAA First Round |publisher=Denver Pioneers |date=May 3, 2015 |accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref> They went on to win the NCAA title, defeating Maryland in the final at Lincoln Financial Field and becoming the first-ever NCAA men's lacrosse champion from outside the [[Eastern Time Zone]].<ref name=\"2015 title\"/>\n\n==Season Results==\nThe following is a list of Denver's season results since becoming a NCAA Division II program in 1991 and becoming a full member of Division I in 1999:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Denver Pioneers|Season|Coach|Overall|Conference|Standing|Postseason}}\n|- align=\"center\"\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead|\n |name= Jon Bock\n |conference= [[Rocky Mountain Lacrosse Conference|Rocky Mountain Intercollegiate Lacrosse League]]\n |startyear=1990\n |endyear=1991\n|}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       = 1991\n | name         = Jon Bock\n | overall      = 6\u20135\n | conference   = 6\u20132\n | confstanding = \n | postseason   =\n | championship =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name      